descript.abstract: This feature class contains lines depicting contacts and faults in the Geologic Map of the Tuba City 30' x 60' Quadrangle, Coconino County, Northern Arizona.Version 1.1, March, 2014- Minor edits were made to the geodatabase to correct geology and facilitate edgematch with adjacent USGS maps.- The database was upgraded from ArcGIS 9.3 to ArcGIS 10.2. This upgrade may have caused some loss to metadata. See FGDC read-only version at the bottom of this page for the original report in its entirety.- Changes made to the geodatabase are not reflected in the pamphlet or on map sheet PDFs.
descript.purpose: This geodatabase and accompanying pamphlet provide information on the geologic structure and stratigraphy of the area and are intended to be of use both in the scientific community and within the context of resource management activities in the area.
descript.supplinf:
This feature class (tubaglg_arc) is a component of the geodatabase of the Geologic Map of the Tuba City 30' x 60' Quadrangle, Coconino County, Northern Arizona. The structure of this geodatabase and its associated feature classes, as well as the feature class naming conventions, loosely follows The National Park Service Geologic Resources Inventory Geology-GIS Geodatabase Data Model (V. 2.1), which can be found at: http://science.nature.nps.gov/im/inventory/geology/docs/gri_gdb_ggdm_v2dot1.pdf
The geodatabase includes the following: structure data (tubaatd) folds (tubafld) geologic contacts and faults (tubaglg_arc) geologic unit polygons (tubaglg_poly24k) geologic unit labels (tubaglg_pt) fractures (tubagln) karst features (tubakar) mines (tubamin) volcanic vents (tubavpf)
Annotation feature classes: dip and fault offset annotation (tubaatdAnno) geologic unit annotation (tubaglg_ptAnno)
Relationship classes: tubaatdAnno - links tubaatd to tubaatdAnno tubaglg_ptAnno - links tubaglg_pt to tubaglg_ptAnno
Related tables: list of map units (tuba_lmu)

attracc.attraccr: The lines in this feature class were mapped at 1:24,000-scale, digitized and attributed in ArcMap, and then visually reviewed for accuracy against the original source maps.

dataqual.logic:
This feature class has been reviewed and is considered to be error-free. The length, position, directionality, and attributes for each line segment have been cross-checked against the source maps and are deemed valid. Segments making up the boundaries of a polygon tie end-to-end to completely enclose the area. Geologic lines attributed as "contact" do not separate geologic map units of the same type. Intersecting lines are separated into individual line segments at the point of intersection.
Topology was created and validated using the following rules: Must not self overlap Must not self-intersect Must not intersect or touch interior Must not have dangles Must be single part Must not have pseudos
dataqual.complete: This feature class is considered complete. All geologic contacts and faults depicted on the source maps were digitized and attributed.

horizpa.horizpar: The positional accuracy of geologic contacts and faults varies as a function of topography and geology. Contacts and faults that occur in bedrock in moderate terrain are considered to be accurately located, and within +/- 12 meters of their actual location on the topographic base map. This accuracy diminishes in areas where the topography is either flat or very steep. Contacts between surficial units are often difficult to discern, and are considered to be approximately located, despite being attributed as accurately located. The 1:24,000 topographic maps and corresponding Digital Raster Graphics (DRGs) that were used as the primary mapping base for this project were assumed to meet the National Map Accuracy Standard of +/- 12 meters.

procstep.procdesc: Geologic contacts and faults were either observed in the field or located from aerial photographs. Data was digitized as a line feature class, then symbolized and checked against the souce maps for accuracy.

altsys.altenc: Explicit elevation coordinate included with horizontal coordinates

attrdomv.udom: Sequential unique whole numbers that are automatically generated.

attr.attrdef: Type of geologic contact or fault. Match values in this field to tubacity100k.style for cartographic symbolization.

edom.edomvd: Boundary between two mapped units that retains the original depositional or intrusive relationship. The contact has been observed and is accurately located.

Structural boundary between mapped units or structural discontinuity within a mapped unit that has experienced relative offset on either side of the fault. The fault has been observed and is accurately located. Displacement of the fault is normal, with the hanging wall moved downward relative to the footwall. Dip of the fault plane is greater that 45°.
Segment of a normal fault that is concealed by a surficial geologic unit. The fault trace is projected to the surface from beneath the mapped surficial unit.

Structural boundary between mapped units or structural discontinuity within a mapped unit that has experienced relative offset on either side of the fault. The existence and location of the fault are inferred from indirect evidence. Displacement on the fault is inferred to be normal, with the hanging wall moved downward relative to the footwall. Dip of the fault plane is inferred to be greater than 45°.
Line representing the extent of the mapped area.

attr.attrdef: Line ornamentation for display and plotting.

edom.edomvd: Bar and ball ornament used to symbolize the downthrown side of a fault.
